post_text: Lester Prairie Schools will start the 2020-21 school year in a hybrid model due to the rise in positive COVID-19 case rates in McLeod County. Grades PreK through 3 will attend every day and do hybrid learning within the building. Grades 4 through 12 will attend every other day on alternating maroon and gold days. September 8th is a maroon day. Please do not respond to this post. If you have questions, please call the school or visit the school's website for more information.

post_text:
Reminder: Lester Prairie Public Schools are closed starting March 18 until March 27. There will not be instructional services or homework during these days. Students should have all of their textbooks at home. Please keep books in a safe place in the event we will need to implement Distance Learning instruction that would start on March 30. More information on Distance Learning will be communicated at a later date.

Lester Prairie Schools will be continuing food service to school age children in our district. Breakfast and lunch meals will be done in a take out style from Door F by the flagpole on the West side of the school for all school age students that attend Lester Prairie Schools. You will pay your normal breakfast and/or lunch rate. We will need you to fill out a Food Service Request Form located on the main page of the District website. Your student‚Äôs lunch ID number will be required to pick up lunch and breakfast meals. Pick up times will be between 9am and 11am.

post_text: These Lester Prairie Kindergarten children enjoyed sledding during their last day of classes in December 2019. School had already provided them with many opportunities to "slide" into new learning experiences. Also, like sledding, they often had to pick themselves up and take on the challenge of learning new skills. This was all very exciting for them and they are ready to take on the challenges and learn all they possibly can during 2020! Happy New Year!

post_text:
‚ÄúRecycle paper? - How can we do that?‚Äù

Puzzled kindergarten children asked that question recently when Mrs. Smith told them, before embarking on a science lesson, that they would be doing just that. Nevertheless, they were eager to jump right in and test out the idea.
First, they tore newspaper into tiny pieces. Then they mixed the pieces of paper with water and put it all in a blender. The result was a wet pulp. The children drained the water from the pulp using metal screens and let the pulp dry. The result---PAPER!
text:
